{The Netherlands had not participated in 1933 and 1935. This time they did,
but world champion Euwe was active in Nottingham. Van Scheltinga was a solid
player.} 1. c4 e6 2. e4 d5 3. cxd5 exd5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nxd5 6. Be2 $5 {
White plays a timid opening.} Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 Nf4 $5 9. Bc4 Nd3 $5 10.
Qb3 Nc5 11. Qc2 Be6 {The manoeuvres have led to equality.} 12. Be2 $6 {
White should exchange the bishops.} Nc6 $1 13. d4 $6 {
There is no need to sacrifice a pawn.} (13. Rd1 $1 Nb4 14. Qb1 Ncd3 15. a3 Nxc1
16. Rxc1 Nc6 17. Qe4 {repairs the problem.}) 13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Be3
$6 (15. Nb5 $1 Qe5 16. f4 Qe4 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxc7 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 Nf2+ 20. Rxf2
Bxf2 21. Nxa8 Rxa8 22. Bf3 {wins back the material.}) 15... Qe5 $1 16. Bxc5 $2
{White gives up the two bishops.} Qxc5 17. Qe4 Qb4 18. Qf3 $5 b6 19. b3 Bf6 20.
Rac1 Bxc3 $5 {Black surrenders a part of the advantage for the exchanges.} 21.
Qxc3 Qxc3 22. Rxc3 c5 23. Rd1 Rfd8 24. Rcd3 Rxd3 25. Bxd3 Kf8 26. Be2 Ke7 27.
f4 Rd8 28. Rxd8 Kxd8 {Theo has an extra pawn in the bishop ending.} 29. Kf2 Ke7
30. Ke3 Bd5 31. g4 $6 {The pawn goes one square too far.} f6 32. h4 Kd6 33. Bb5
h6 34. h5 $5 Bc6 35. Be2 b5 36. Kd2 Bd7 37. Kc3 (37. a3 $1 a5 38. Kc3 b4+ 39.
axb4 axb4+ 40. Kd2 Be6 41. Kc2 Bd5 {also wins for Black.}) 37... b4+ $1 38. Kd2
Bc6 39. Ke3 Bd5 40. Bb5 a5 41. Be2 a4 $1 42. Bd1 a3 $1 43. Kd3 Be6 (43... Be6
44. f5 Bd5 {leads to zugzwang, because the white king has to cover c4 and his
bishop should protect b3 and f3.} 45. Be2 $5 Bxb3 $1) 0-1

