(Van den Tol - Vinken, Leiden 1946).}) 11. e4 Bd6 12. O-O Rg8 13. Qe2 Qa5 14.
Nd2 $1 O-O-O $6 {The black king experiences more safety in the centre.} 15. Nc4
Qc7 16. f4 c5 17. a3 $1 {Botvinnik starts an attack on the queenside.} f5 $2 ({
Preferable is} 17... Kb8 $1 18. axb4 cxd4) 18. axb4 Nf6 $5 (18... cxd4 19. Rxa7
$1 Bxb4 20. Bd2 $1 Qc5 21. Rfa1 {
directs all white pieces towards the queenside.}) 19. Na5 $2 (19. bxc5 $1 Be7
20. Ne5 $1 {overwhelms the opponent.}) 19... c4 $1 {
Minev avoids the immediate loss.} 20. Nxb7 cxd3 21. Nxd6+ Rxd6 22. Qxd3 fxe4
23. Qe2 Qb7 $5 24. f5 $1 Nd5 {Minev carries  out another desperate defence.}
25. Qxe4 Nxb4 26. Qxb7+ Kxb7 27. fxe6 fxe6 28. Rf7+ Kc6 29. Be3 Kd5 30. Rxh7
Nc6 31. Bf4 $5 Rdd8 32. Bc7 $6 (32. h4 $1 Kxd4 33. Bg5 Rd5 34. Re1 $1 e5 35.
Rc7 {wins easily.}) 32... Rh8 $1 33. Rg7 Rhg8 34. Rh7 Rh8 35. Rg7 Rhg8 36. Rf7
Rgf8 37. Raf1 Rxf7 38. Rxf7 Rc8 39. Be5 $5 {
The alternative is an advance of the h-pawn.} Nxd4 40. Bxd4 Kxd4 41. Kf2 $5 {
The a-pawn could be captured.} a5 42. g4 $5 ({Better is} 42. Kf3 Rb8 43. Rd7+
Ke5 44. Rd2) 42... Rc2+ 43. Kg3 Rxb2 44. g5 a4 $6 {
The g-pawn should be stopped.} 45. g6 $1 Rb1 $6 46. Kh4 $2 {
Botvinnik gives this move an acclamation mark.} (46. g7 $1 a3 47. Kg2 Rb2+ 48.
Kh3 $1 Rb3+ 49. Kh4 {wins elegantly.}) 46... Rg1 $1 47. Kh5 Kc4 48. Rf4+ Kb5 $2
(48... Kb3 $1 49. Rg4 Rxg4 50. Kxg4 a3 51. g7 a2 52. g8=Q a1=Q 53. Qxe6+ Kb4 {
leads to a draw, according to the modern theory.}) 49. Rf3 $2 ({Better is} 49.
Kh6) 49... Kb4 50. Rf4+ Kb5 $2 51. Rf3 $2 Kb4 52. Rg3 Rxg3 53. hxg3 a3 54. g7
a2 55. g8=Q a1=Q 56. Qg4+ $5 Ka5 57. Qxe6 {
A draw has arisen. The rest can be found on a CD-Rom.} Qh8+ 58. Kg6 Qc3 59. g4
Qd2 60. g5 Qd4 $2 61. Qf5+ $2 (61. Kh7 $1 Qh4+ 62. Qh6 {
leads to a mate in 64 moves theoretically.}) 61... Ka4 62. Kh5 Qh8+ 63. Kg4 Qh1
$2 64. Qf4+ $1 Ka5 65. Qe5+ Ka4 66. g6 Qd1+ 67. Kg5 Qd8+ 68. Kf5 Qc8+ 69. Kf4
Qc1+ 70. Qe3 Qc7+ 71. Qe5 Qc1+ 72. Kf5 Qc8+ 73. Kg5 Qd8+ 74. Qf6 Qd5+ 75. Qf5
Qd8+ 76. Kh5 Qe8 77. Qf4+ $2 Ka5 $4 ({Right is} 77... Ka3 $1 78. Qc1+ Ka2 {
and the black king cannot be attacked by the combined forces of the white king
and queen.}) 78. Qd2+ $1 {White can mate in 35 moves.} Ka4 79. Qd4+ Ka5 80. Kg5
$1 Qe7+ 81. Kf5 Qf8+ 82. Ke4 $1 Qh6 83. Qe5+ Ka4 84. g7 Qh1+ 85. Kd4 Qd1+ 86.
Kc5 Qc1+ 87. Kd6 Qd2+ 88. Ke6 Qa2+ 89. Qd5 Qe2+ 90. Kd6 $1 Qh2+ 91. Kc5 $1 {
White threatens to queen the pawn. If Black checks, White can exchange.  
World champion Botvinnik played and analysed an excellent game for his days.
Nowadays, the analytical results are completely different.} 1-0

