{4500 people came to watch in Siegen, when Spassky and Fischer played their
game. Both men were very nervous.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5.
e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Qc7 11. Rc1 Rd8 12.
h3 ({Boris played} 12. Qe1 {against Bobby in Santa Monica 1966 and won.}) 12...
b6 13. f4 e6 14. Qe1 Na5 15. Bd3 f5 {
Fischer seeks a revenge for the previous loss.} 16. g4 $5 {
Spassky makes an aggressive new move.} fxe4 17. Bxe4 Bb7 18. Ng3 Nc4 19. Bxb7
$5 Qxb7 20. Bf2 Qc6 21. Qe2 $5 {Boris wants to attack.} (21. Qe4 Qxe4 22. Nxe4
cxd4 23. cxd4 {equalises.}) 21... cxd4 22. cxd4 b5 23. Ne4 $6 {
White sacrifices a pawn for the initiative.} (23. Rfe1 Bxd4 24. Qxe6+ {
leads to simplification.}) 23... Bxd4 24. Ng5 Bxf2+ 25. Rxf2 Rd6 $6 ({
Spassky prefers} 25... Re8) 26. Re1 Qb6 27. Ne4 $6 {Black gets a new chance.} (
27. f5 $1 Rf8 28. Nxe6 Rd2 {brings exchanges.}) 27... Rd4 $6 (27... Rc6 {
protects pawn e6.}) 28. Nf6+ $1 Kh8 29. Qxe6 Rd6 $1 ({Not} 29... Rd1 $2 30. Qf7
$3 Rxe1+ 31. Kg2 Ne3+ 32. Kf3 $3 Qc6+ 33. Kg3 Rg1+ 34. Kh4 Rxg4+ 35. hxg4 Qh1+
36. Kg5 Nxg4 37. Kxg4 Qg1+ 38. Kf3 Qh1+ 39. Kg3 Rd8 {
and White has a material plus (Vasiukov and Speelman)} 40. Nd7) 30. Qe4 Rf8 $6
31. g5 Rd2 32. Ref1 Qc7 $2 {Fischer collapses at the end of the game.} ({
Better is} 32... Rc8 33. Qe7 Qc7) 33. Rxd2 Nxd2 34. Qd4 $1 Rd8 $2 ({Correct is
} 34... Qb6 $1 35. Qxb6 axb6 36. Rd1 Rd8 37. Kg2 Rd4 38. Re1 $1 {
and White has winning chances (Spassky).}) 35. Nd5+ Kg8 36. Rf2 $1 Nc4 37. Re2
Rd6 ({Or} 37... Qb6 38. Re8+ $1) 38. Re8+ Kf7 39. Rf8+ $1 {Black will lose his
queen in two moves.   Reshevsky drew quickly. The other games were drawn after
a hard fight. So the Soviet Union defeated the USA. Spassky told me that he
was superior to Fischer  in 1970, but this had turned around in 1972.} 1-0

